ing forces were selected. He was Lieutenant of the Eldest Train Band at Milford in October 1698, and was elected Deputy from Milford to the Connecticut General Assembly in May 1700."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"No will — his son Joseph administered","body":"No will of Joseph is on record. His inventory was taken March 21, 1703/4. His widow Mary and son Joseph were appointed administrators, though the son was still a minor at the time."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00096","display_label":"Both destroyed the Wepawaug fort — fined £10.","link_text":"John Fowler"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Joseph Platt","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"Platt","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"joseph-platt-1649"},"X00077":{"id":"X00077","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X00076","date_year":1680,"location_city":"Milford","location_county":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["I00064","I00021"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Families of Early Milford, Connecticut","platform":"Ancestry.com"}],"marriage_date":{"year":1680,"month":5,"day":5},"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Two daughters each married a Newton first cousin","body":"Her daughters Phebe and Hannah both married into the Newton family — Phebe to Samuel Newton, Hannah to Samuel's first cousin Fletcher Newton. 